CRC Card 1: Transponder_Simulator
• Class: Transponder_Simulator
• Responsibilities:
– Simulate an aircraft's transponder.
– Generate a high-density data packet containing aircraft type, flight ID, altitude, speed, heading, and position.
– Broadcast the data packet at regular intervals.
• Collaborators:
– Aircraft_Data_Packet
Assumption: The problem describes the transponder as part of the arriving aircraft. This class represents that external entity within our system's model.


CRC Card 2: Ground_Station_Receiver
• Class: Ground_Station_Receiver
• Responsibilities:
– Listen for and receive raw data packets from aircraft transponders.
– Unpack the high-density packet into its individual data fields.
– Pass the unpacked data to the system for processing.
• Collaborators:
– Transponder_Simulator (as data source)
– Aircraft_Data_Packet
– Flight_Data_Processor


CRC Card 3: Aircraft_Data_Packet
• Class: Aircraft_Data_Packet
• Responsibilities:
– Represent the raw data received from a transponder.
– Hold the byte-level data structure of the transmission.
• Collaborators:
CRC Card 4: Flight_Data_Processor
• Class: Flight_Data_Processor
• Responsibilities:
– Receive unpacked flight data from the ground station.
– Validate the incoming data for completeness and errors.
– Translate data into a format for storage.
– Send validated flight data to the tracker for storage.
• Collaborators:
– GroundStationReceiver
– Flight_Record
– Aircraft_Tracker
CRC Card 5: Flight_Record
• Class: Flight_Record
• Responsibilities:
– Store the state of a single aircraft at a point in time.
– Hold attributes like flight ID, aircraft type, altitude, speed, heading, timestamp, and position.


CRC Card 6: Aircraft_Tracker
• Class: Aircraft_Tracker
• Responsibilities:
– Keep the main record of every present flight detail.
– Refresh the saved facts for a specific aircraft using fresh input.
– Make a new FlightRecord the moment an aircraft gets initially seen.
– Give flight details toward other system sections when asked.
• Collaborators:
– Flight_Record
– Flight_Data_Processor
– Collision_Detector
– Display_Updater
– Query_Handler

CRC Card 7: Display_Updater
• Class: Display_Updater
• Responsibilities:
– Start a display update process each 10 seconds.
– Fetch the most recent group of all flight information from the tracker.
– Prepare the gathered information for the visual presentation.
– Pass the prepared data toward the renderer for showing on the screen.
• Collaborators:
– System_Clock (implicit)
– Aircraft_Tracker
– Screen_Renderer

CRC Card 8: Screen_Renderer
• Class: Screen_Renderer
• Responsibilities:
– Handle the visual presentation window and the drawing environment.
– Put plane symbols, names, and routes onto the picture.
– Make planes that face danger stand out (for example, alter their hue).
• Collaborators:
– Display_Updater
– Danger_Alert

CRC Card 9: Collision_Detector
• Class: Collision_Detector
• Responsibilities:
– Constantly examine present flight details for risky scenarios.
– Look for possible crashes (missing the required distance) between sets of planes.
– Look for other risks (like being too close to ground or limited areas).
– Make a Danger_Alert item when a risk is found.
• Collaborators:
– Aircraft_Tracker
– Airspace_Map
– Danger_Alert

CRC Card 10: Danger_Alert
• Class: Danger_Alert
• Responsibilities:
– Encapsulate information about a detected dangerous situation.
– Store the involved aircraft, the type of alert, and the severity.
– Notify the display system to highlight the relevant aircraft.
• Collaborators:
– ScreenRenderer

CRC Card 11: Airspace_Map
• Class: Airspace_Map
• Responsibilities:
– Keep static facts concerning the airport's location.
– Set out physical limits, forbidden areas, and ground elevations.
– Give details regarding areas to the Collision_Detector.
• Collaborators:
– Collision_Detector

CRC Card 12: Query_Handler
• Class: Query_Handler
• Responsibilities:
– Get and make sense of requests from the controller's screen.
– Figure out which plane the controller needs data for.
– Pull the full flight data out of the tracker module.
– Shape the specifics (such as using plain text) and forward them toward the controller's screen for viewing.
• Collaborators:
– Controller_Console
– Aircraft_Tracker

CRC Card 13: Controller_Console
• Class: Controller_Console
• Responsibilities:
– Stand for the way the controller puts information in and gets output.
– Record what the controller does, such as selecting an aircraft or typing an ID number.
– Give the data request over to the Query_Handler component.
– Show the full flight data that the handler sends back.
• Collaborators:
– Query_Handler
